            , <rs id="t17791208-4-cd15" type="crimeDate">Nov. 21st</rs>
                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17791208-4-off14 t17791208-4-cd15"></join>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17791208-4-person70">
                  NICHOLAS
                   FUGE
               <interp inst="t17791208-4-person70" type="surname" value="FUGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791208-4-person70" type="given" value="NICHOLAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791208-4-person70" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>On the 4th of November last, towards the morning, I met the prisoner and another <rs id="t17791208-4-deflabel16" type="occupation">soldier</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17791208-4-defend67 t17791208-4-deflabel16"></join> in Pall-Mall.</p>
               <p>What are you? - I am a <rs id="t17791208-4-viclabel17" type="occupation">gentleman's servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17791208-4-victim69 t17791208-4-viclabel17"></join>. I had just come out of my place, but was engaged to another service. I wanted a lodging; they offered to procure me a lodging in <placeName id="t17791208-4-crimeloc18">Gardener's-lane, Westminster</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17791208-4-crimeloc18" type="placeName" value="Gardener's-lane, Westminster"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17791208-4-crimeloc18" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17791208-4-off14 t17791208-4-crimeloc18"></join>. I went there with them. After I had been there half an hour, the prisoner went down; I desired him to bring up a candle; he came up again without one; he then laid hold of me in the dark, put his hand into my breeches pocket, and took out what money I had, which was two shillings and sixpence. I had my clothes on, I had not undressed myself. After he had taken my money he went and fetched a candle and locked the door, drew his bayonet and swore he would have my life or I should give him my great coat and boots; he struck me, gave me three wounds upon my head, besides several bruises upon my body; the other man stood by, but said nothing. 
               <persName id="t17791208-4-person71">
                  John
                   Petit
               <interp inst="t17791208-4-person71" type="surname" value="Petit"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791208-4-person71" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791208-4-person71" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             came and got me out of the room. I had been drinking about two pots of beer in the evening, but was not the worse for liquor.</p>
               <p>Was the prisoner intoxicated? - I do not know that the prisoner was drunk.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17791208-4-person72">
                  JOHN
                   PETIT
               <interp inst="t17791208-4-person72" type="surname" value="PETIT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791208-4-person72" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791208-4-person72" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a soldier. I was in bed at the house. I was getting up to work in the morning, for I work in the coal trade when I am not upon duty; I heard a bustle in the room for a quarter of an hour; then I went into the room to get my accountrements out of it, and I saw the Prosecutor all over blood, and the prisoner with a drawn bayonet in his hand; upon seeing this I immediately wrested the bayonet out of his hand, and got the prosecutor out of the room, so as to part them, that they should not have any more struggling together.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17791208-4-person73">
                  WILLIAM
                   JENKINS
               <interp inst="t17791208-4-person73" type="surname" value="JENKINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791208-4-person73" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791208-4-person73" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>The prisoner, between five and six in the morning, came to my lodging, it is a house that takes in lodgers; he came for a light; he said d - n it, I have got a man in the room, and I will have his great coat and boots, and every meg he has. I took the light from him. I heard a noise in the next room; I heard the prisoner d - n the prosecutor, and ask him for his gold and great coat and boots, or else he swore he would have his life.</p>
               <p>PRISONER's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>This man met me in the street at three o'clock in the morning and asked me if I<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177912080005"></xptr>would have part of a pot of beet; I said no, I had plenty of beer; he said you may as well go and have a pot somewhere; I said there was never a house open; he replied there was a house open in the Haymarket; we went there and had three pots of beer; coming along the Haymarket again he asked me if I lodged by myself; I said I did then, because the man I lodged with was gone to the hospital; I told him he was a stranger to me, but if he would accept of a night's lodging, he was very welcome; he went home with me. After I went up into the room I pulled my coat off and went down into the necessary; when I returned again into the room, he said he had lost his money out of his pocket, and he accused me of taking it; I said it was a wrong thing. I did not say any thing that I would have his money and boots and things. I was much in liquor; if I had an unlawful weapon in my hand, it is more than I know of. I never had my hand in his pocket.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17791208-4-verdict19" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17791208-4-verdict19" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>Tried by the First Middlesex Jury before Mr. Justice BLACKSTONE.</p>
